5: Are you praying today as well, Cran?
9:
Ah, Stella. No, just spreading my
wings in the wind for a bit.
16:
Yes. To us birdfolk, the wind is a
revered ally.
19:
When I feel the wind, it reminds me
of someone.
24:
I suppose you could say that. I've
known him since I was a child.
25:
He was the strongest hunter our
clan had ever seen—his eyes and
wings were unparalleled.
28:
Despite this, he never takes anything
seriously—to the point of even
taking names while flying.
35:
Even the elders were unable to keep
him under control. I, being close to
his age, was chosen to be a
caretaker of sorts.
36:
Of course, at first all I wished to know
were the secrets behind his
incredible talents.
41: Yes. And a dear friend as well.
43:
In the end, I could never catch up to
him.
50:
Despite losing to someone you
considered to be your rival, you...
51: You don't seem to be upset about it.
54:
Funny, is it not? I often wonder why
myself.
57:
The breeze in my wings—it takes me
back a time where I would cut
through the wind at blistering
speeds in a futile attempt to keep
up with him.
63:
He must be someone important to
you.
70:
Perhaps this could be considered a
type of prayer as well.
71:
This way of thinking of someone
might not be recognized as prayer
by my people, but to me... it is just as
important.
76:
Do you think you could teach me
how to pray as well?
80: I was hoping to try it myself.
83:
O-of course! There are many ways
you can pray, but I would be glad to
teach you how I do it!
88:
Excellent. Now let go and move as
you see fit.
90: Who will you pray for, I wonder?
100:
It's almost suppertime. Thanks to
Cran, we've got a pretty meaty
catch to feast on tonight!
103: So come and get it while it's hot!
110:
There were too many for me to
count. Is there a limit to how many
people I can pray for?
113:
Of course not, Stella. In fact, the very
fact you have so many people in
your life to pray for is a blessing in
itself.
